{{Infobox scientist | image = | name = Nicolas Tadeusz Courtois | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1971|11|14}} | birth_place = [[Lębork]] | residence = | citizenship = [[France|French]] | field = [[Computer science]] | work_institutions = [[University College London]] | alma_mater = [[University of Paris|University of Paris VI: Pierre et Marie Curie]]<ref name="doctoral-degree">{{mathgenealogy|id=138172|name=Nicolas T. Courtois}}</ref> | known_for = [[Cryptography]], [[security]] | website= | signature = }}
'''Nicolas Tadeusz Courtois''' (born 14 November 1971) is a [[cryptographer]], a senior lecturer in computer science at [[University College London]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Staff profile|url=http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/people/N.Courtois.html|publisher=UCL|accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref>
Courtois was one of the co-authors of both the [[XSL attack]] against [[block cipher]]s such as the [[Advanced Encryption Standard]]<ref>{{citation | last1 = Courtois | first1 = Nicolas T. | last2 = Pieprzyk | first2 = Josef | contribution = Cryptanalysis of block ciphers with overdefined systems of equations | doi = 10.1007/3-540-36178-2_17 | pages = 267–287 | publisher = Springer-Verlag | series = [[Lecture Notes in Computer Science]] | title = Advances in Cryptology – AsiaCrypt 2002 | volume = 2501 | year = 2002}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|title=New AES crypto standard broken already? Depends who you ask|publisher=[[The Register]]|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2002/09/16/new_aes_crypto_standard_broken/|first=Thomas C.|last=Greene|date=September 16, 2002}}.</ref> and the XL system for solving systems of algebraic equations,<ref>{{citation | last1 = Courtois | first1 = Nicolas | last2 = Klimov | first2 = Alexander | last3 = Patarin | first3 = Jacques | last4 = Shamir | first4 = Adi | author4-link = Adi Shamir | contribution = Efficient algorithms for solving overdefined systems of multivariate polynomial equations | doi = 10.1007/3-540-45539-6_27 | pages = 392–407 | publisher = Springer-Verlag | series = Lecture Notes in Computer Science | title = Advances in Cryptology – EuroCrypt 2000 | volume = 1807 | year = 2000}}.</ref> used in the attack. Other cryptographic results of Courtois include algebraic attacks on [[stream cipher]]s,<ref>{{citation | last = Courtois | first = Nicolas T. | doi = 10.1007/978-3-540-45146-4_11 | title = Advances in Cryptology – Crypto 2003 | series = Lecture Notes in Computer Science | pages = 176–194 | publisher = Springer-Verlag | contribution = Fast algebraic attacks on stream ciphers with linear feedback | volume = 2729 | year = 2003}}.</ref> attacks on the [[KeeLoq]] and Hitag 2 systems used for [[remote keyless system|remote keyless automobile entry systems]],<ref name="clone">{{citation|title=Oyster cracker vows to clone cards: Cloning kit could sell for just £200, says researcher|publisher=v3.co.uk|url=http://www.v3.co.uk/vnunet/news/2222625/oyster-cracker-clone-cards|first=Robert|last=Blincoe|date=July 28, 2008}}.</ref> and an analysis of cryptographic weaknesses in [[public transit]] [[smart card]]s including the [[London Underground]] [[Oyster card]]<ref>{{citation|title=Researchers crack Oyster card security|publisher=v3.co.uk|url=http://www.v3.co.uk/vnunet/news/2219828/london-oyster-cracked|date=June 23, 2008|first=Andrew|last=Charlesworth}}.</ref> and the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[OV-chipkaart]].<ref name="clone"/><ref>{{citation|title=Weer nieuwe kraak chip OV-chipkaart|journal=WebWereld|date=April 18, 2008|url=http://webwereld.nl/nieuws/50715/weer-nieuwe-kraak-chip-ov-chipkaart.html|language=Dutch|first=Brenno|last=de Winter}}.</ref> More recently, he has written about [[cryptocurrency]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Emerging Technology From the arXiv|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/view/527346/other-interesting-arxiv-papers-week-ending-may-10-2014/|publisher=MIT Technology Review|accessdate=2 June 2014|date=17 May 2014|quote=On The Longest Chain Rule and Programmed Self-Destruction of Crypto Currencies}}</ref>
Courtois graduated from [[University of Paris|University of Paris VI: Pierre et Marie Curie]], where he got his doctoral degree in cryptography.<ref name="doctoral-degree" />
